group.label: How should I use this form?

input.label: Not all browsers work smoothly with this tool. **Chrome v.78 and Firefox v.70** have been successfully tested so far

You can find **Save as Draft** option at the end of the form (i.e. go to Submission on your top right navigation menu). Please, note that it will be stored as cookies in your browser so you should finish using the same computer and browser (check top left corner to open your draft)
You can **Save as PDF** to get a local copy before you submit your data (i.e. click the printer logo next to your top right navigation menu)
Once you have completed the form, you can click **Submit** at the end of the form (i.e. go to Submission on your top right navigation menu)

**Note**: If you have question, comment or want to make changes to the data after Submission, please, reach [David Terol](mailto://david.terol@philips.com) or [Sundaresan Jagadeesan](sundaresan.j@philips.com)
This questionnaire is built using Open Source Software [KoBoToolbox](https://www.kobotoolbox.org/)
It does not intend to replace interactive Software Center of Excellence assessment process but to help preparation and creation of more consistent data

The self-assessment framework and tools, like all SW CoE assessments, is assessing the maturity of a sub-set of your practices. It is not related to any of your products, solutions, projects or services and says nothing auditable about the quality, safety or compliance of the SW that you produce. **It should not form part of your QMS** and any tools provided by the SW CoE to help capture self-assessment are not validated.
High level example indicators that the Philips SW Centre of Excellence uses when assessing software craftsmanship maturity scores
Technology stacks, products and businesses are diverse at Philips great craftsmanship can mean different things in different contexts
Meeting all example indicators is not a guarantee of a particular score it is a starting point for the discussion

Craftsmanship scoring will be a discussion if you have good reasons and supporting data for your approach, even if it does not align with this framework, you may still be scoring high for craftsmanship
Your improvement proposals and any feedback are welcome
**D (Initial)**: Ad hoc or lenient with minimal supporting data. Basic tools in standard configurations. Small subset of products/requirements/codebase. Some local advocacy

**C (Basic)**: Basic policy with basic supporting data. Tool choice & configurations support policy and some modernization activity. (guide) > 60% (of intended scope subset) of products/requirements/code. Local training, coaching and advocacy

**B (Advanced)**: Ambitious policy and detailed and trended supporting data. Occasional data-driven policy adaptions. Generalist and specialist tools and custom tools and/or custom configurations and continuous modernization. (guide) > 80% (of intended scope subset)products/requirements/codebase. Share across BG and with other BGs. Some external voice.

**A (Differentiator)**: Innovative policy and supporting data techniques. Frequent data-driven policy adaptions. Innovative tooling & configurations. Near 100% (of intended scope subset) products/requirements/codebase. Extensive internal and external voice. "Thought Leader".

More details in [Software Excellence Scoring Framework Guidance](https://share.philips.com/:p:/r/sites/STS020170706072003/Public%20Repository/Software%20Excellence%20Scoring%20Framework.pptx?d=wd4307231f46b4f4d838ab849ce28cf92&csf=1&e=37GdVr)
